\begin_layout Section
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Introduction"

\end_inset

Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Today most web applications use 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

cookies
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to associate HTTP requests with 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

sessions
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 A 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

session
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is a set of related HTTP requests (and responses), where the relation is
 to some request(s) that created the session.
 Some sessions are created by the act of authenticating a user, in which
 case the primary goal of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

sessions
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is to avoid having to re-authenticate the user on every request.
 Other times a session is created when a request is received that is not
 associated with any session, in which case the primary purpose of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

sessions
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 may be to provide a pseudonymous identifier for an otherwise anonymous
 user.
 We call the mechanisms by which requests are strung into sessions 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

session continuation
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Cookies
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 are server-assigned bearer tokens -- nothing more, nothing less, though
 some cookies are used just to store things like 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

shopping cart
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 state.
 A bearer token is an octet blob which can be presented as-is, possibly
 repeatedly, to authenticate a user to some party; mere possession of the
 bearer token is sufficient to act on the user's behalf to at least one
 service.
 As such they are susceptible to theft via passive attacks (eavesdropping)
 if not protected in some other way (e.g., by using TLS), or via active attacks
 such as BEAST and CRIME [http://www.xors.me/?attachment_id=3727], as well
 as to leakage in various ways [XXX expand].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We would like a session continuation mechanism to replace or augment cookies
 that has better security semantics than bearer tokens.
 In particular we would like a system that is not susceptible to theft via
 active attacks like BEAST and CRIME.
 We believe that such a scheme should use cryptographic algorithms and cryptogra
phic session keys, and should be amenable to being keyed by HTTP- and web-authen
tication mechanisms.
 A new session continuation mechanism should be suitable for use in web
 and non-web HTTP applications, and should work even for unauthenticated
 sessions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Motivation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The motivation for this document and the related session continuation protocol
 
\begin_inset Flex EntityXRef
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
